'''Saad Esporte Clube''', usually known simply as '''Saad''', is a [[List of women's football clubs in Brazil|Brazilian]] [[women's football (soccer)|women's football]] team, from [[S<U+00E3>o Caetano do Sul]], [[S<U+00E3>o Paulo (state)|S<U+00E3>o Paulo]] state.

==History==
On [[April 28]], [[1961]], Saad Esporte Clube was founded by the businessman Fel<U+00ED>cio Jos<U+00E9> Saad. The club was founded as a replacement for another club, S<U+00E3>o Bento, which folded in the previous decade.<ref name="clubhistoryofficialwebsite">{{cite web |url=http://www.saadec.com.br/portugues/historia/historia.php |title=Hist<U+00F3>rico: 45 Anos |accessdate=2007-09-20 |format= |work=Saad Esporte Clube }}</ref>

In 1985, the club started a women's football section, and four year later, in 1989, its men's football section was closed.<ref name="clubhistoryofficialwebsite"/>

In 1996, Saad won the [[Campeonato Brasileiro de Futebol Feminino|Brazilian Women's Football Championship]], organized by the [[Brazilian Football Confederation]].<ref name="campeonatobrasileiro">{{cite web |url=http://paginas.terra.com.br/esporte/rsssfbrasil/tables/brwcamp.htm |title=Brazil - List of Women's Champions |accessdate=2007-09-20 |format= |work=RSSSF }}</ref>

In [[Copa do Brasil de Futebol Feminino 2007|2007]], as Mato Grosso do Sul/Saad, the club won the [[Copa do Brasil de Futebol Feminino]].<ref name="copadobrasildefutebolfeminino">{{cite web |url=http://oglobo.globo.com/esportes/mat/2007/12/08/327514354.asp |title=Saad conquista o t<U+00ED>tulo da primeira Copa do Brasil feminina |accessdate=2007-12-10 |format= |work=O Globo Online}}</ref>

==Achievements==
* [[Copa do Brasil de Futebol Feminino]]: [[Copa do Brasil de Futebol Feminino 2007|2007]]
* [[Campeonato Brasileiro de Futebol Feminino|Brazilian Women's Football Championship]]: 1996
* [[Campeonato Brasileiro de Futebol Feminino|Brazilian Women's Football Circuit]]: 2003
* [[Campeonato Brasileiro de Futebol Feminino|Brazil Trophy]]: 1989

